    <note>Li(2) Shang [18101] See documentation for great grandsons, Youzhi [18104] and Youren [19864]. The history of his descendants illustrates a number of characteristics of one type of elite lineage. His great grandson, Youzhi and Youzhi's father and grandfather all held office, but only Youzhi earned the jinshi--Youzhi was Shi(5) Hao's [8113] son-in-law and the father-in-law of another member of the distinguished Mingzhou Shi(5). Shang's son, Yi(13) [19861], did not hold office, but had a posthumous title--probably on the basis of his collateral kin's achievements. Yi(13)'s son, Yang(3) [19862], was a local gentry of wealth (In fact, Sun(1) Yingshi [16663], in his funerary inscription for Yang(3)'s son, Youren, notes that the Yuyao Li(2) were a family of wealth (fujia) and this is the ancestral status used for this lineage. Yang(3) employed Sun(1) Jie [16659], father of Yingshi, as the teacher in the lineage school (jiashu). Youren was also not employed in government, but devoted his life to literary pursuits. Another son of Shang, Hong(5) [19863], pursued a military career.</note>
